05458nam a22007575i 9780748679607DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222007stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486796077 a10.1515/97807486796072doi  a(DE-B1597)616223  a(OCoLC)1306540366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPER0030002bisacsh1 aRalph, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Art that all Arts do Approve :bManifestations of the Dance Impulse in High Renaissance Culture: Studies in Honour of Margaret M McGowan: Dance Research Volume 25 Issue 2 /cRichard Ralph. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDance Research Special Issues : DRSI00tContents -- tEditorial Introduction. Margaret M. McGowan: Pioneer of Academic Dance Research -- tThe Barriers: From Combat to Dance (Almost) -- t‘Rules for Design’: Beauty and Grace in Caroso’s Choreographies -- tFragment of the Sovereign as Hermaphrodite: Time, History, and the Exception in Le Ballet de Madame -- tDancing Towards Death: Masques and Entertainments in London and Florence as precedents for Thomas Middleton’s Women Beware Women -- tBurlesque Ballet, a Ballad and a Banquet in Ben Jonson’s The Gypsies Metamorphos’d (1621) -- tFrom Tragicomedy to Epic: The Court Ballets of Desmarets de Saint-Sorlin -- tJean II Berain’s Costume Designs for the Ballet Les Plaisirs de la Paix (1715) -- tInto the Labyrinth: Kenneth MacMillan and his Ballets -- tThe Publications of Margaret M. McGowan0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMargaret McGowan is the doyenne of British dance historians; in celebration of her long and distinguished career and to coincide with its Silver Anniversary, the scholarly journal Dance Research has invited a number of distinguished dance historians and colleagues working in arts cognate with dance to contribute essays in her honour. The connecting theme is dance as an over-arching and stimulating agent, contributing to cultural and intellectual life during the early modern period in ways that were broader and more profound in their influence than is often recognised. These essays reveal an art that in the early stages of its development invariably resonated with 'context', and was widely exploited for social and political purposes. Contributions explore the nature of dance forms and, in explaining their evolution, highlight the discovery of significant links between rhetoric, discourses on art and architecture, and the language used by dancing masters. In paying tribute to a major pioneer in the discipline of dance studies, this study presents a compelling argument for the universality of dance, for its character as central to human experience, and for its power to stimulate endeavour across an unexpectedly broad front of experience and expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / General.2bisacsh1 aAnglo, Sydney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanova-Green, Marie-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrisp, Clement, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe La Gorce, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranko, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulryne, J. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevile, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavelhofer, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShewring, Margar